# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dashboard-design
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] A **bullet graph** is a variation of a bar graph developed by Stephen Few.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] Seemingly inspired by the traditional thermometer charts and progress bars found in many dashboards, the bullet graph serves as a replacement for dashboard gauges and meters.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs were developed to overcome the fundamental issues of gauges and meters: they typically display too little information, require too much space, and are cluttered with useless and distracting decorations.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] The qualitative ranges are displayed as varying intensities of a single hue to make them discernible by those who are color blind and to restrict the use of colors on the dashboard to a minimum.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs can be created in R (programming language) using the bulletgraph() function developed by Marco Torchiano.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] Below is an example of R code using the bulletgraph() function to create a black-and-white and colored bullet graph.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs may be horizontal or vertical and may be stacked to allow comparisons of several measures at once.
[src:dashboard-design/bullet-graph] More information about bullet graphs can be found in the book *Information Dashboard Design* by Stephen Few.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:dashboard-design/dashboard-business] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Markings and visual elements can be called chartjunk if they are not part of the minimum set of visuals necessary to communicate the information understandably.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Another kind of chartjunk skews the depiction and makes it difficult to understand the real data being displayed.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Examples of this type include items depicted out of scale to one another, noisy backgrounds making comparison between elements difficult in a chart or graph, and 3-D simulations in line and bar charts.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] The term *chartjunk* was coined by Edward Tufte in his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* based on ideas and materials developed for a Princeton statistics course co-taught with John Tukey.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] The term has been associated with Tufte in other references.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] In *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* Tufte claims that good design is founded in minimalist design principles.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Specifically, he states that "graphics reveal data" if they are designed with "graphical integrity." Tufte, through minimalist design principles, was committed to an objective and neutral values of science.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Other researchers have argued that minimalism is not objective and is full of its own rhetoric and potential to bias.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Tufte, in coining the term chartjunk, also made direct comments about a well-known designer at that time, Nigel Holmes.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] This debate between Tufte and Holmes is emblematic of the tension between statistical and designerly approaches to visualization design.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] The term chartjunk is an umbrella term that can be used to describe a variety of visual devices and has been referenced by different terms across research.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Alternative terms include *embellishment,* *excessive annotation*, decoration, *extraneous elements*, and *unnecessary ornamentation*.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] Robert Kosara, also a data visualization practitioner, researcher, and author of the blog EagerEyes, noted that not all chartjunk are the same, some are harmful (e.g. a busy background), others harmless (e.g. nice borders or pictures), and some even helpful (e.g. annotations).
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] In a recent study by Parsons and Shukla, they interviewed data visualization designers and found that there is both a "corrective movement" in the design community to move away from minimalist design principles, but also, that designers had different definitions for what constitutes chartjunk.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] The information visualization research community has researched the effects of chartjunk on how viewers interpret visualizations.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] There have been studies that found that chartjunk increases long-term memorability of the chart.
[src:dashboard-design/data-ink-ratio] A recent study found that chartjunk, in the form of semantically meaningful icons, increased accessibility of charts for people with Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities (IDD).
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics have been around for many years and recently the increase of the number of easy-to-use, free tools have made the creation of infographics available to a large segment of the population.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Social media sites such as Facebook and Twitter have also allowed for individual infographics to be spread among many people around the world.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics are widely used in the age of short attention span.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In newspapers, infographics are commonly used to show the weather, as well as maps, site plans, and graphs for summaries of data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Some books are almost entirely made up of information graphics, such as David Macaulay's *The Way Things Work*.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The Snapshots in *USA Today* are also an example of simple infographics used to convey news and current events.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Modern maps, especially route maps for transit systems, use infographic techniques to integrate a variety of information, such as the conceptual layout of the transit network, transfer points, and local landmarks.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Public transportation maps, such as those for the Washington Metro and the London Underground map, are well-known infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Public places such as transit terminals usually have some sort of integrated "signage system" with standardized icons and stylized maps.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1626, Christoph Scheiner published the *Rosa Ursina sive Sol*, a book that revealed his research about the rotation of the sun.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics appeared in the form of illustrations demonstrating the Sun's rotation patterns.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1786, William Playfair, an engineer and political economist, published the first data graphs in his book *The Commercial and Political Atlas*.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] To represent the economy of 18th century England, Playfair used statistical graphs, bar charts, line graphs, area charts, and histograms.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In his work, *Statistical Breviary*, he is credited with introducing the first pie chart.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Around 1820, modern geography was established by Carl Ritter.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] His maps included shared frames, agreed map legends, scales, repeatability, and fidelity.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Such a map can be considered a "supersign" which combines sign systems—as defined by Charles Sanders Peirce—consisting of symbols, icons, indexes as representations.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Other examples can be seen in the works of geographers Ritter and Alexander von Humboldt.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1857, English nurse Florence Nightingale used information graphics to persuade Queen Victoria to improve conditions in military hospitals.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The principal one she used was the Coxcomb chart, a combination of stacked bar and pie charts, depicting the number and causes of deaths during each month of the Crimean War.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] 1861 saw the release of an influential information graphic on the subject of Napoleon's disastrous march on Moscow.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term "graph" in 1878 in the scientific magazine *Nature* and published a set of diagrams showing the relationship between chemical bonds and mathematical properties.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] These were also some of the first mathematical graphs.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1900, the African-American historian, sociologist, writer, and Black rights activist, W.E.B.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Du Bois presented data visualizations at the Exposition Universelle (1900) in Paris, France.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In addition to curating 500 photographs of the lives of Black Americans, Du Bois and his Atlanta University team of students and scholars created 60 handmade data visualizations to document the ways Black Americans were being denied access to education, housing, employment, and household wealth.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The Cologne Progressives developed an aesthetic approach to art that focused on communicating information.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Gerd Arntz, Peter Alma and Augustin Tschinkel, all participants in this movement were recruited by Otto Neurath for the Gesellschafts- und Wirtschaftsmuseum, where they developed the Vienna Method from 1926 to 1934.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Here simple images were used to represent data in a structured way.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Following the victory of Austrofascism in the Austrian Civil War, the team moved to the Netherlands where they continued their work rebranding it Isotypes (International System of Typographic Picture Education).
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The method was also applied by IZOSTAT (ИЗОСТАТ) in the Soviet Union.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1942 Isidore Isou published the Lettrist manifesto, a document covering art, culture, poetry, film, and political theory.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The included works also called metagraphics and hypergraphics, are a synthesis of writing and visual art.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1958 Stephen Toulmin proposed a graphical argument model, called The Toulmin Model of Argumentation.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The diagram contained six interrelated components used for analyzing arguments and was considered Toulmin's most influential work, particularly in the field of rhetoric, communication, and computer science.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The Toulmin Model of Argumentation became influential in argumentation theory and its applications.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In 1972 and 1973, respectively, the Pioneer 10 and Pioneer 11 spacecraft included on their vessels the Pioneer Plaques, a pair of gold-anodized aluminum plaques, each featuring a pictorial message.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The pictorial messages included nude male and female figures as well as symbols that were intended to provide information about the origin of the spacecraft.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The images were designed by Carl Sagan and Frank Drake and were unique in that their graphical meanings were to be understandable to extraterrestrial beings, who would have no conception of human language.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] A pioneer in data visualization, Edward Tufte, wrote a series of books – *Visual Explanations*, *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, and *Envisioning Information* – on the subject of information graphics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Referred to by The New York Times as the "da Vinci of Data", Tufte began to give day-long lectures and workshops on the subject of infographics starting in 1993.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] As of 2012, Tufte still gives these lectures.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] To Tufte, good data visualizations represent every data point accurately and enable a viewer to see trends and patterns in the data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Tufte's contribution to the field of data visualization and infographics is considered immense, and his design principles can be seen in many websites, magazines, and newspapers today.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The infographics created by Peter Sullivan for The Sunday Times in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s were some of the key factors in encouraging newspapers to use more infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Sullivan is also one of the few authors who have written about information graphics in newspapers.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Likewise, the staff artists at USA Today, the United States newspaper that debuted in 1982, established the goal of using graphics to make information easier to comprehend.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, the paper has received criticism for oversimplifying news stories and for creating infographics that some find emphasizes entertainment over content and data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Tufte coined the term chartjunk to refer to graphics that are visually appealing to the point of losing the information contained within them.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] With vector graphics and raster graphics becoming ubiquitous in computing in the 21st century, data visualizations have been applied to commonly used computer systems, including desktop publishing and Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Closely related to the field of information graphics is information design, which is the creation of infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] By the year 2000, Adobe Flash-based animations on the Internet had made use of many key practices in creating infographics in order to create a variety of products and games.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Likewise, television began to incorporate infographics into the viewers' experiences in the early 2000s.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] One example of infographics usage in television and in pop culture is the 2002 music video by the Norwegian musicians of Röyksopp, for their song "Remind Me." The video was composed entirely of animated infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Similarly, in 2004, a television commercial for the French nuclear technology company Areva used animated infographics as an advertising tactic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Both of these videos and the attention they received have conveyed to other fields the potential value of using information graphics to describe complex information efficiently.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] With the rise of alternatives to Adobe Flash, such as HTML 5 and CSS3, infographics are now created in a variety of media with a number of software tools.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The field of journalism has also incorporated and applied information graphics to news stories.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] For stories that intend to include text, images, and graphics, the system called the maestro concept allows entire newsrooms to collaborate and organize a story to successfully incorporate all components.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Across many newsrooms, this teamwork-integrated system is applied to improve time management.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The maestro system is designed to improve the presentation of stories for busy readers of media.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Many news-based websites have also used interactive information graphics in which the user can extract information on a subject as they explore the graphic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Many businesses use infographics as a medium for communicating with and attracting potential customers.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Information graphics are a form of content marketing and have become a tool for internet marketers and companies to create content that others will link to, thus possibly boosting a company's reputation and online presence.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Religious denominations have also started using infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] For example, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has made numerous infographics to help people learn about their faith, missionaries, temples, lay ministry, and family history efforts.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics are finding a home in the classroom as well.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Courses that teach students to create their own infographics using a variety of tools may encourage engagement in the classroom and may lead to a better understanding of the concepts they are mapping onto the graphics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] With the popularity of social media, infographics have become popular, often as static images or simple web interfaces, covering any number of topics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Such infographics are often shared between users of social networks such as Facebook, Twitter, Pinterest, Google+ and Reddit.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The hashtag #infographic was tweeted 56,765 times in March 2012 and at its peak 3,365 times in a span of 24 hours.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The three parts of all infographics are the visual, the content, and the knowledge.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The visual consists of colors and graphics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] There are two different types of graphics – theme, and reference.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] These graphics are included in all infographics and represent the underlying visual representation of the data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Reference graphics are generally icons that can be used to point to certain data, although they are not always found in infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Statistics and facts usually serve as the content for infographics and can be obtained from any number of sources, including census data and news reports.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] One of the most important aspects of infographics is that they contain some sort of insight into the data that they are presenting – this is the knowledge.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics are effective because of their visual element.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Humans receive input from all five of their senses (sight, touch, hearing, smell, taste), but they receive significantly more information from vision than any of the other four.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Fifty percent of the human brain is dedicated to visual functions, and images are processed faster than text.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The brain processes pictures all at once, but processes text in a linear fashion, meaning it takes much longer to obtain information from text.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Entire business processes or industry sectors can be made relevant to a new audience through a guidance design technique that leads the eye.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The page may link to a complete report, but the infographic primes the reader making the subject-matter more accessible.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Online trends, such as the increasingly short attention span of Internet users, has also contributed to the increasing popularity and effectiveness of infographics.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] When designing the visual aspect of an infographic, a number of considerations must be made to optimize the effectiveness of the visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The six components of visual encoding are spatial, marks, connection, enclosure, retinal properties, and temporal encoding.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Each of these can be utilized in its own way to represent relationships between different types of data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, studies have shown that spatial position is the most effective way to represent numerical data and leads to the fastest and easiest understanding by viewers.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Therefore, the designers often spatially represent the most important relationship being depicted in an infographic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] There are also three basic provisions of communication that need to be assessed when designing an infographic – appeal, comprehension, and retention.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] "Appeal" is the idea that communication needs to engage its audience.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Comprehension implies that the viewer should be able to easily understand the information that is presented to them.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] And finally, "retention" means that the viewer should remember the data presented by the infographic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The order of importance of these provisions depends on the purpose of the infographic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] If the infographic is meant to convey information in an unbiased way, such as in the domains of academia or science, comprehension should be considered first, then retention, and finally, appeal.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, if the infographic is being used for commercial purposes, then appeal becomes most important, followed by retention and comprehension.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] When infographics are being used for editorial purposes, such as in a newspaper, the appeal is again most important but is followed first by comprehension and then retention.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, the appeal and the retention can in practice be put together with the aid of a comprehensible layout design.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Recently, as an attempt to study the effect of the layout of an infographic on the comprehension of the viewers, a new Neural Network-based cognitive load estimation method was applied on different types of common layouts for the infographic design.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] When the varieties of factors listed above are taken into consideration when designing infographics, they can be a highly efficient and effective way to convey large amounts of information in a visual manner.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Data visualizations are often used in infographics and may make up the entire infographic.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] There are many types of visualizations that can be used to represent the same set of data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Therefore, it is crucial to identify the appropriate visualization for the data set and infographic by taking into consideration graphical features such as position, size, shape, and color.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] There are primarily five types of visualization categories – time-series data, statistical distributions, maps, hierarchies, and networking.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Time-series data is one of the most common forms of data visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Examples of graphics in this category include index charts, stacked graphs, small multiples, and horizon graphs.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Index charts are ideal to use when raw values are less important than relative changes.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] It is an interactive line chart that shows percentage changes for a collection of time-series data based on a selected index point.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] For example, stock investors could use this because they are less concerned with the specific price and more concerned with the rate of growth.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Stacked graphs are area charts that are stacked on top of each other, and depict aggregate patterns.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] They allow viewers to see overall patterns and individual patterns.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, they do not support negative numbers and make it difficult to accurately interpret trends.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] An alternative to stacked graphs is small multiples.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Instead of stacking each area chart, each series is individually shown so the overall trends of each sector are more easily interpreted.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Horizon graphs are a space efficient method to increase the data density of a time-series while preserving resolution.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Statistical distributions reveal trends based on how numbers are distributed.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Common examples include histograms and box-and-whisker plots, which convey statistical features such as mean, median, and outliers.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In addition to these common infographics, alternatives include stem-and-leaf plots, Q–Q plots, scatter plot matrices (SPLOM) and parallel coordinates.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] For assessing a collection of numbers and focusing on frequency distribution, stem-and-leaf plots can be helpful.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The numbers are binned based on the first significant digit, and within each stack binned again based on the second significant digit.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] On the other hand, Q–Q plots compare two probability distributions by graphing quantiles against each other.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] This allows the viewer to see if the plot values are similar and if the two are linearly related.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] SPLOM is a technique that represents the relationships among multiple variables.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] It uses multiple scatter plots to represent a pairwise relation among variables.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Another statistical distribution approach to visualize multivariate data is parallel coordinates.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Rather than graphing every pair of variables in two dimensions, the data is repeatedly plotted on a parallel axis, and corresponding points are then connected with a line.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] The advantage of parallel coordinates is that they are relatively compact, allowing many variables to be shown simultaneously.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Maps are a natural way to represent geographical data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Time and space can be depicted through the use of flow maps.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Line strokes are used with various widths and colors to help encode information.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Choropleth maps, which encode data through color and geographical region, are also commonly used.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Graduated symbol maps are another method to represent geographical data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] They are an alternative to choropleth map and use symbols, such as pie charts for each area, over a map.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] This map allows for more dimensions to be represented using various shapes, sizes, and colors.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Cartograms, on the other hand, completely distort the shape of a region and directly encode a data variable.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Instead of using a geographic map, regions are redrawn proportionally to the data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] For example, each region can be represented by a circle and the size/color is directly proportional to other information, such as population size.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Many data sets, such as spatial entities of countries or common structures for governments, can be organized into natural hierarchies.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Node-link diagrams, adjacency diagrams, and enclosure diagrams are all types of infographics that effectively communicate hierarchical data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Node-link diagrams are a popular method due to the tidy and space-efficient results.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] A node-link diagram is similar to a tree, where each node branches off into multiple sub-sections.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] An alternative is adjacency diagrams, which is a space-filling variant of the node-link diagram.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Instead of drawing a link between hierarchies, nodes are drawn as solid areas with sub-sections inside of each section.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] This method allows for size to be easily represented than in the node-link diagrams.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Enclosure diagrams are also a space-filling visualization method.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, they use containment rather than adjacency to represent the hierarchy.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Similar to the adjacency diagram, the size of the node is easily represented in this model.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Network visualization explores relationships, such as friendships and cliques.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Three common types are force-directed layout, arc diagrams, and matrix view.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Force-directed layouts are a common and intuitive approach to network layout.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] In this system, nodes are similar to charged particles, which repel each other.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Links are used to pull related nodes together.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Arc diagrams are one-dimensional layouts of nodes with circular arcs linking each node.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] When used properly, with good order in nodes, cliques and bridges are easily identified in this layout.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Alternatively, mathematicians and computer scientists more often use matrix views.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Each value has an (x,y) value in the matrix that corresponds to a node.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] By using color and saturation instead of text, values associated with the links can be perceived rapidly.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] While this method makes it hard to view the path of the nodes, there are no line crossings, which in a large and highly connected network can quickly become too cluttered.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] While all of these visualizations can be effectively used on their own, many modern infographics combine multiple types into one graphic, along with other features, such as illustrations and text.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Some modern infographics do not even contain data visualization, and instead are simply a colorful and succinct ways to present knowledge.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Fifty-three percent of the 30 most-viewed infographics on the infographic sharing site visual.ly did not contain actual data.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Comparison infographics are a type of visual representation that focuses on comparing and contrasting different elements, such as products, services, options, or features.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] These infographics are designed to help viewers make informed decisions by presenting information in a clear and concise manner.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Comparison infographics can be highly effective in simplifying complex data and highlighting key differences between multiple items.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Infographics can be created by hand using simple everyday tools such as graph paper, pencils, markers, and rulers.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] However, today they are more often created using computer software, which is often both faster and easier.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] They can be created with general illustration software.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Diagrams can be manually created and drawn using software, which can be downloaded for the desktop or used online.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Templates can be used to get users started on their diagrams.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] Additionally, the software allows users to collaborate on diagrams in real time over the Internet.
[src:dashboard-design/infographic] There are also numerous tools to create very specific types of visualizations, such as creating a visualization based on embedded data in the photos on a user's smartphone.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Visualization today has ever-expanding applications in science, education, engineering (e.g., product visualization), interactive multimedia, medicine, etc.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Typical of a visualization application is the field of computer graphics.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The invention of computer graphics (and 3D computer graphics) may be the most important development in visualization since the invention of central perspective in the Renaissance period.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The development of animation also helped advance visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The use of visualization to present information is not a new phenomenon.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] It has been used in maps, scientific drawings, and data plots for over a thousand years.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Examples from cartography include Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century AD), a map of China (1137 AD), and Minard's map (1861) of Napoleon's invasion of Russia a century and a half ago.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Most of the concepts learned in devising these images carry over in a straightforward manner to computer visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Edward Tufte has written three critically acclaimed books that explain many of these principles.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Computer graphics has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the publication of Visualization in Scientific Computing, a special issue of Computer Graphics.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Since then, there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH, devoted to the general topic, and special areas in the field, for example volume visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Most people are familiar with the digital animations produced to present meteorological data during weather reports on television, though few can distinguish between those models of reality and the satellite photos that are also shown on such programs.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] TV also offers scientific visualizations when it shows computer drawn and animated reconstructions of road or airplane accidents.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Some of the most popular examples of scientific visualizations are computer-generated images that show real spacecraft in action, out in the void far beyond Earth, or on other planets.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Dynamic forms of visualization, such as educational animation or timelines, have the potential to enhance learning about systems that change over time.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Apart from the distinction between interactive visualizations and animation, the most useful categorization is probably between abstract and model-based scientific visualizations.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The abstract visualizations show completely conceptual constructs in 2D or 3D.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] These generated shapes are completely arbitrary.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The model-based visualizations either place overlays of data on real or digitally constructed images of reality or make a digital construction of a real object directly from the scientific data.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is usually done with specialized software, though there are a few exceptions, noted below.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Some of these specialized programs have been released as open source software, having very often its origins in universities, within an academic environment where sharing software tools and giving access to the source code is common.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] There are also many proprietary software packages of scientific visualization tools.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Models and frameworks for building visualizations include the data flow models popularized by systems such as AVS, IRIS Explorer, and VTK toolkit, and data state models in spreadsheet systems such as the Spreadsheet for Visualization and Spreadsheet for Images.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] As a subject in computer science, scientific visualization is the use of interactive, sensory representations, typically visual, of abstract data to reinforce cognition, hypothesis building, and reasoning.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is the transformation, selection, or representation of data from simulations or experiments, with an implicit or explicit geometric structure, to allow the exploration, analysis, and understanding of the data.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization focuses and emphasizes the representation of higher order data using primarily graphics and animation techniques.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] It is a very important part of visualization and maybe the first one, as the visualization of experiments and phenomena is as old as science itself.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Traditional areas of scientific visualization are flow visualization, medical visualization, astrophysical visualization, and chemical visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] There are several different techniques to visualize scientific data, with isosurface reconstruction and direct volume rendering being the more common.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Data visualization is a related subcategory of visualization dealing with statistical graphics and geospatial data (as in thematic cartography) that is abstracted in schematic form.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to explore large amount of abstract data.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The term "information visualization" was originally coined by the User Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC and included Jock Mackinlay.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Practical application of information visualization in computer programs involves selecting, transforming, and representing abstract data in a form that facilitates human interaction for exploration and understanding.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Important aspects of information visualization are dynamics of visual representation and the interactivity.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Strong techniques enable the user to modify the visualization in real-time, thus affording unparalleled perception of patterns and structural relations in the abstract data in question.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Educational visualization is using a simulation to create an image of something so it can be taught about.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] This is very useful when teaching about a topic that is difficult to otherwise see, for example, atomic structure, because atoms are far too small to be studied easily without expensive and difficult to use scientific equipment.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The use of visual representations to transfer knowledge between at least two persons aims to improve the transfer of knowledge by using computer and non-computer-based visualization methods complementarily.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Thus properly designed visualization is an important part of not only data analysis but knowledge transfer process, too.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Knowledge transfer may be significantly improved using hybrid designs as it enhances information density but may decrease clarity as well.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] For example, visualization of a 3D scalar field may be implemented using iso-surfaces for field distribution and textures for the gradient of the field.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Examples of such visual formats are sketches, diagrams, images, objects, interactive visualizations, information visualization applications, and imaginary visualizations as in stories.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] While information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to derive new insights, knowledge visualization focuses on transferring insights and creating new knowledge in groups.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Beyond the mere transfer of facts, knowledge visualization aims to further transfer insights, experiences, attitudes, values, expectations, perspectives, opinions, and estimates in different fields by using various complementary visualizations.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Product visualization involves visualization software technology for the viewing and manipulation of 3D models, technical drawing and other related documentation of manufactured components and large assemblies of products.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] It is a key part of product lifecycle management.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Product visualization software typically provides high levels of photorealism so that a product can be viewed before it is actually manufactured.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] This supports functions ranging from design and styling to sales and marketing.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] *Technical visualization* is an important aspect of product development.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Originally technical drawings were made by hand, but with the rise of advanced computer graphics the drawing board has been replaced by computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] CAD-drawings and models have several advantages over hand-made drawings such as the possibility of 3-D modeling, rapid prototyping, and simulation.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] 3D product visualization promises more interactive experiences for online shoppers, but also challenges retailers to overcome hurdles in the production of 3D content, as large-scale 3D content production can be extremely costly and time-consuming.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] In recent years, product visualization has increasingly incorporated interactive and real-time technologies, particularly in e-commerce environments.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Modern 3D visualization tools enable users to explore products in detail, customize attributes such as color, materials, and configuration, and view items in simulated or real-world contexts.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] These capabilities enhance user engagement and support more informed decision-making by providing realistic and context-aware representations of products.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] As a result, product visualization can help reduce uncertainty prior to purchase and contribute to lower product return rates.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Visual communication is the communication of ideas through the visual display of information.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Primarily associated with two dimensional images, it includes: alphanumerics, art, signs, and electronic resources.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Recent research in the field has focused on web design and graphically oriented usability.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics focuses on human interaction with visualization systems as part of a larger process of data analysis.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics has been defined as "the science of analytical reasoning supported by the interactive visual interface".
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Its focus is on human information discourse (interaction) within massive, dynamically changing information spaces.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics research concentrates on support for perceptual and cognitive operations that enable users to detect the expected and discover the unexpected in complex information spaces.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Technologies resulting from visual analytics find their application in almost all fields, but are being driven by critical needs (and funding) in biology and national security.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] One particular type of interactive visualization is virtual reality (VR), where the visual representation of information is presented using an immersive display device such as a stereo projector (see stereoscopy).
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Another type of interactive visualization is collaborative visualization, in which multiple people interact with the same computer visualization to communicate their ideas to each other or to explore information cooperatively.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Frequently, collaborative visualization is used when people are physically separated.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Using several networked computers, the same visualization can be presented to each person simultaneously.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The people then make annotations to the visualization as well as communicate via audio (i.e., telephone), video (i.e., a video-conference), or text (i.e., IRC) messages.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The Programmer's Hierarchical Interactive Graphics System (PHIGS) was one of the first programmatic efforts at interactive visualization and provided an enumeration of the types of input humans provide.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] All of these actions require a physical device.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Input devices range from the common – keyboards, mice, graphics tablets, trackballs, and touchpads – to the esoteric – wired gloves, boom arms, and even omnidirectional treadmills.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] These input actions can be used to control both the unique information being represented or the way that the information is presented.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] When the information being presented is altered, the visualization is usually part of a feedback loop.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] For example, consider an aircraft avionics system where the pilot inputs roll, pitch, and yaw and the visualization system provides a rendering of the aircraft's new attitude.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Another example would be a scientist who changes a simulation while it is running in response to a visualization of its current progress.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] This is called *computational steering*.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] More frequently, the representation of the information is changed rather than the information itself.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Experiments have shown that a delay of more than 20 ms between when input is provided and a visual representation is updated is noticeable by most people .
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Thus it is desirable for an interactive visualization to provide a rendering based on human input within this time frame.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] However, when large amounts of data must be processed to create a visualization, this becomes hard or even impossible with current technology.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Thus the term "interactive visualization" is usually applied to systems that provide feedback to users within several seconds of input.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The term *interactive framerate* is often used to measure how interactive a visualization is.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Framerates measure the frequency with which an image (a frame) can be generated by a visualization system.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] A framerate of 50 frames per second (frame/s) is considered good while 0.1 frame/s would be considered poor.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The use of framerates to characterize interactivity is slightly misleading however, since framerate is a measure of bandwidth while humans are more sensitive to latency.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Specifically, it is possible to achieve a good framerate of 50 frame/s but if the images generated refer to changes to the visualization that a person made more than 1 second ago, it will not feel interactive to a person.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] The rapid response time required for interactive visualization is a difficult constraint to meet and there are several approaches that have been explored to provide people with rapid visual feedback based on their input.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] *Progressive rendering* – where a framerate is guaranteed by rendering some subset of the information to be presented and providing incremental (progressive) improvements to the rendering once the visualization is no longer changing.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] *Level-of-detail (LOD) rendering* – where simplified representations of information are rendered to achieve a desired framerate while a person is providing input and then the full representation is used to generate a still image once the person is through manipulating the visualization.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] Subsampling can also be used to accelerate rendering techniques such as volume visualization that require more than twice the computations for an image twice the size.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] By rendering a smaller image and then scaling the image to fill the requested screen space, much less time is required to render the same data.
[src:dashboard-design/interactive-visualization] *Frameless rendering* – where the visualization is no longer presented as a time series of images, but as a single image where different regions are updated over time.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] A **sparkline** is a very small line chart, typically drawn without axes or coordinates.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] It presents the general shape of a variation (typically over time) in some measurement, such as temperature or stock market price, in a simple and highly condensed way.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Whereas a typical chart is designed to professionally show as much data as possible, and is set off from the flow of text, sparklines are intended to be succinct, memorable, and located where they are discussed.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Sparklines are small enough to be embedded in text, or several sparklines may be grouped together as elements of a small multiple.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] In 1762 Laurence Sterne used typographical devices in his sixth volume of The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman to illustrate his narrative proceeding: "These were the four lines I moved through my first, second, third, and fourth volumes,–".
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] The 1888 monograph describing the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa shows barometric signatures of the event obtained at various stations around the world in the same fashion, but in separate plates (VII & VIII), not within the text.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Edward Tufte documented a compact style in 1983 called "intense continuous time-series".
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] He introduced the term *sparkline* in 2006 for "small, high resolution graphics embedded in a context of words, numbers, images", which are "data-intense, design-simple, word-sized graphics".
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Later in 2020, Tufte attributed the idea to Donald Knuth's "METAFONTbook".
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] The first software sparkline was programmed in 1999 by Peter Zelchenko.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] He introduced "an inline-chart" feature for Mike Medved's QuoteTracker.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] TD Ameritrade later discontinued QuoteTracker.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] On May 7, 2008, Microsoft employees filed a patent application for the implementation of sparklines in Microsoft Excel 2010.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] The application was published on November 12, 2009, prompting Tufte to express concerns about patent breadth and non-novelty.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] On 23 January, 2009, MultiRacio Ltd. published an OpenOffice.org Calc extension named "EuroOffice Sparkline".
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] On March 3, 2022, Tomaž Vajngerl implemented sparklines in LibreOffice Calc version 7.4, including support for importing sparklines from the OOXML Workbook format.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Sparklines are frequently used in line with text.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] The sparkline should be about the same height as the text around it.
[src:dashboard-design/sparkline] Tufte offers some useful design principles for the sizing of sparklines to maximize their readability.
